4700.name: The North Gate of Aina
4700.description:
This is within the high, arched entrance into the port city of Aina.
Great stone gargoyles guard the gate on either side and seem to watch over
the road into the city. The gates stand open, but they appear thick and
sturdy, and would be impossible to break through if they were shut. A wide,
rocky road leads away from the city to the north, leading towards the Pardor
Mountains in the distance. To the south, just within the arch in the Town
Square, and beyond that, the winding streets of the city.

4701.name: Gate Square
4701.description:
This wide, cobbled square marks the entrance into the port city of Aina.
Wide, winding streets lead away to the south, east and west among the tall
buildings and to the north are the gates of the city, the entrance guarded by
two enormous stone gargoyles. The buildings and shops around the square are
as varied and as unusual as the people. Some of them have solid, rock
fronts, reminiscent of the gothic structures of ages past, while others
bear the more modern polished fronts which hint at elegance.

4702.name: Wall Road
4702.description:
This is a narrow road which leads east and west between the city walls and
the backs of various buildings which stand to the south. The position of the
street means that it is in almost constant shadow during the day. A few
lanterns hang from wall brackets but that does little to dispel the night
shadows. To the west stands the Gate Square.

4703.name: Wall Road
4703.description:
This part of Wall Road is better lighted and more populated than the rest of
it, but this is probably due to the guard post which can just be made out
at the end of the road to the east. On one side of the road are the backs of
various tall buildings and to the north is the city wall, both barriers
effectively serving to block out the majority of the light. The road leads
both east and west from here.

4704.name: Wall Road
4704.description:
To the east of here is a small intersection with another road that goes
south into Aina's poor district. The road is in a bad state of affair, and
though it is more populated than the rest of the street, it is still an
unsafe road to travel along. Wall Road leads to the east and the west from
here.

4705.name: An Intersection on Wall Road
4705.description:
A small, dirty, cramped street leads south from here, into the poor district
of the city. Even from here many of the buildings can be seen to look
Wall road leads to the east from here, towards a guard post which is set
into the wall at the end of the street, and west, following the wall.

4706.name: Wall Road
4706.description:
From here, Wall Road leads to the east and the west, following the line of
the great northern wall of the city. On the opposite side of the street,
the backs of tall building tower over the road, blocking out the light
during most of the day. Just east of here another small road leads to the
south into the poorer sections of the city.

4707.name: Wall Road
4707.description:
A small road leads south from here into the poor district of the city. The
sign beside the street reads: Penny Avenue, and the narrow, cramped road
looks dirty and in a bad state of repair. Wall Road leads west from here,
following the city wall in the direction of the entrance gate. To the east
is a small, but fully manned Guard Station.

4708.name: A Guard Station
4708.description:
This small building is a guard station, built for use by the patrolling
city guards. It is sparsely furnished but not completely devoid of home
comforts. A fireplace has been built on one wall and it crackles quietly.
A wooden table and chairs rest in the centre of the room, the chairs both
currently unoccupied.

4709.name: Rogue's Alley
4709.description:
This dirty, narrow little alleyway runs to the south and joins up with
Wall Road to the north. The backs of tall buildings are on either side,
close together and blocking out most of the light. A strange smell comes
from piles of discarded litter on the ground and the occasional rat can
be seen shuffling through the refuse.

4710.name: Penny Avenue
4710.description:
This is the northern end of Penny Avenue, a narrow street running north and
south through the poor district of the city. The houses and shops along the
roadside are badly rundown and many of them appear as little more than
hovels. These people out on the streets look downtrodden and unhealthy, many
of them dressed in rags that appear never to have been washed. To the north
is an intersection with Wall Road, and Penny Avenue continues to the south.

4711.name: The Broken Arrow
4711.description:
This rundown inn is one of the worst run establishments in the city. The
walls and windows are streaked with dirt and grime and many of the tables
are chipped or splintered. Foul smoke hangs in a continuous cloud in the
upper part of the room and the smell of the place is nothing short of
disgusting. A filthy, poc-marked counter lines the western wall and the
exit to the tavern lies to the east.

4712.name: Outside a Small Tavern
4712.description:
The small alleyway ends here at a chipped wooden door, a sign above it
proclaiming it to be a tavern: The Broken Arrow. Dirty, fogged windows are
built into the wall next to the door but it is impossible to see through
them. Raised voices and the clanking of ale mugs can be heard from within.
The alley runs a short distance to the east where it joins up with another
running to the north and south.

4713.name: Rogue's Alley
4713.description:
The alleyway continues to the north and the south, passing between the tall,
dark backs of buildings. Another, smaller alley leads to the west and voices
can be heard coming from that direction. Litter and other, more unpleasant
items cover the ground and the smell is strong enough to turn even an
ogre's stomach.

4714.name: Penny Avenue
4714.description:
The rundown, ramshackle buildings on either side of the street give Penny
Avenue a feeling of hopelessness that is reflected on the faces of the
people who live here. Cracks zigzag the walls of many of the hovels and
several of them have broken or missing window panes. The road itself is
cracked and there are many holes in it's surface making it almost impossible
for carts or horses, if any had wanted to travel the road.

4715.name: Steps on the Sea Wall
4715.description:
These stone steps are cut into the Sea Wall, and lead down to a curious
ledge that is cut into the wall about half way down. Below that, the sea
washes up against the stone, occassionally sending waves crashing down on
it. The stone steps lead upwards, back to the wharf.

4716.name: Rogue's Alley
4716.description:
The alley comes to an end here at a tall brick wall. A large pile of litter
and rubbish has been dumped at the foot of the wall and the smell could
almost be described as a physical presence. Flies and a dozen other winged
insects buzz around the disgusting pile. The alleyway continues to the north
between the backs of several buildings.

4717.name: A Curious Stone Ledge
4717.description:
This narrow stone ledge has been cut into the side of the Sea Wall. It
does not appear to serve any obvious purpose, there being no room to moor
a boat, and the ledge leading nowhere. Stone steps lead up from the ledge
to the Wharf, someway above.

exdescs.ledge:
The ledge is wide enough to the west that a single person
could make their way in that direction, being careful with
their footing, though if there is anything to be found there,
that would take some investigating to discover.
exdescs.stone:
The ledge is wide enough to the west that a single person
could make their way in that direction, being careful with
their footing, though if there is anything to be found there,
that would take some investigating to discover.

4718.name: Penny Avenue
4718.description:
Tightly packed buildings crowd the road on either side of it, many of them
in such a bad state of repair that they seem ready to fall down at the
slightest breeze. The road itself leads to the north and south, but it is
cracked and pitted, making travel along its arduous. The people that can
be seen on the road appear ragged and many are in sore need of a meal.

4719.name: Penny Avenue
4719.description:
Penny Avenue ends here and a short distance to the south stands the infamous
Hangman's Square. The Avenue itself leads to the north through a large
section of Aina's poor district, a fact made painfully obvious by the state
of repair of the buildings along the roadside. Many of the people are
dressed in old rags and look pitiful indeed.

4720.name: Hangman's Square
4720.description:
This is Hangman's Square, a large, paved area where the prisoner's of Aina
are brought and hung. The gallows can be seen some way to the west, creaking
slightly in the breeze. To the north runs Penny Avenue, a narrow, rundown
street running through Aina's poor district. Beggar's Row leads to the east
and appears in as bad a condition as Penny.

4721.name: Gallow's Corner
4721.description:
This small corner of Hangman's Square is known as Gallow's Corner, named
after the platform and noose that has stood here for as long as anyone can
remember. There is a large space around the gallows to allow for
spectator's, the gruesome display being a popular pastime among the
population of the poor district. The rest of the square can be reached to
the east.

4722.name: Beggar's Row
4722.description:
This is Beggar's Row, a rundown, refuse ridden street in the poor district.
The buildings are little more than hovels and appear ready to fall down if
a strong breeze blew by. Litter and garbage fill the gutters and the smell
from some of the people is almost enough to empty ones stomach of its
contents. The street continues to the east, while the infamous Hangman's
Square can be accessed to the west.

4723.name: Beggar's Row
4723.description:
Beggar's Row continues to the east and west from here, past rundown, and
in many instances, derelict buildings. The general atmosphere on the street
is one of hoplessness and despair. The people appear worn and bedraggled
and pass by with barely a glance at anything other than the ground. The
small houses and buildings beside the road are ready to collapse and many
are nothing more than shacks.

4724.name: Beggar's Row
4724.description:
Beggar's Row becomes narrower here, if that is possible and passes
between an overhang as two houses connect across the street. The
smell in this small tunnel is nothing less than atrocious, and rats
are everywhere, sniffing at the large piles of refuse that are heaped
against the walls. The road continues to the east and west from here.

4725.name: Beggar's Row
4725.description:
Beggar's Row ends here but a small, rather scruffy looking tavern stands to
the north, the strong smell of ale and smoke wafting from its open doors.
The sign outside declares it to be the Drunken Dragon. Backed up against
the city wall to the east is a small food cart which sells very little
that is edible if the smell is anything to go by. Beggar's Row continues
to the west.

4726.name: The Drunken Dragon
4726.description:
This is the crowded common room of the Drunken Dragon Tavern. The top
half of the room is filled with a constant haze of pipe smoke, which seems
to writhe and turn as though it was alive. The muted voices of the few
patrons and the clanking of ale tankards are the only noises to be heard
from the room, making the place seem more like a morgue than a tavern. The
doorway stands to the south, leading out onto Beggar's Row.

4727.name: A Dark Back Alley
4727.description:
This short alley is littered with refuse and old piles of rotting food. The
smell is nothing short of indescribable, and the flies buzzing around the
area are incredibly bothersome. A cramped shop stands at the end of the dark
alley to the north, and the back entrance to the Drunken Dragon stands to
the south, its muted light spilling out of the open door into the alley.
A second, smaller alley is to the west.

4728.name: A Dead End
4728.description:
The alley comes to an abrupt end here at a blank wall. Rubbish and other
more unpleasant things form a small pile at the base of the wall but other
than that, the alley is more or less empty, not counting the ever present
cloud of buzzing flies. Another dark alley is to the east, bigger than
this but no more cleaner.

exdescs.blank:
The wall is made up from bricks, most of them of uniform size,
except for one in the center of the wall.
exdescs.brick:
One brick in particular is much larger than the rest, and looks
like it isn't mortared in as well as the rest. It makes one almost
want to push it back into the wall.
exdescs.bricks:
One brick in particular is much larger than the rest, and looks
like it isn't mortared in as well as the rest. It makes one almost
want to push it back into the wall.
exdescs.wall:
The wall is made up from bricks, most of them of uniform size,
except for one in the center of the wall.

4729.name: Telvik's Knives
4729.description:
This small hovel serves as a knife shop, the wares stacked crudely and
carelessly on various racks around the interior. Many of them appear blunt
or otherwise useless but there are some that look in fairly good condition.
The location, and muted light in this shop hints that maybe the shop is
not entirely legal. The exit stands to the south, leading into a dark
alleyway.

4730.name: A Food Cart
4730.description:
A cart is pushed up against the city wall here and serves as a stall,
offering food, or the closest thing to food that can be found in the poor
district. An ominous cloud of flies hang over the cart, and if the smell
is not bad enough, the mere appearance of the food could be enough to
turn even an ogre's stomach. Beggar's Row is to the west.

4731.name: Wall Road
4731.description:
This is Wall Road, a narrow road that leads east and west between the city
wall and the backs of houses and buildings to the south. The street is
rarely busy but it is possible to reach several of the city's more popular
districts along several of the intersecting roads. The high walls throw the
street into darkness during most of the day and night, the street lamps
doing little to illuminate the area.

4732.name: Wall Road
4732.description:
This long, narrow street is known as Wall Road, and it travels east and west
between the town wall to the north, and the backs of various buildings to
the south. The confined, narrow space of the street means that it is in
shadow for much of the day, and as such, is not very popular. Lanterns hang
from the wall for use during the night, but many of them have been broken,
and those that haven't give off very little light.

4733.name: Wall Road
4733.description:
Wall Road runs to the east and the west from here, the tall city wall
towering above to the north. Further west can be seen another road
leading away to the south, and it appears to be a busy, popular road. To
the east, the road leads as far as the eye can see.

4734.name: An Intersection on Wall Road
4734.description:
Another wider, busier road intersects Wall Road here and leads south. A sign
on the wall states it to be Merchants Way. From the amount of people visible
on the street, it appears to be an extremely busy thoroughfare, popular for
most of the day. Wall Road itself leads to the east and the west from here,
following the great north wall of the city.

4735.name: Wall Road
4735.description:
This is Wall Road. To the west there is an intersection with Prince Kelmer's
Mile. The great city walls tower over this road, throwing it into shadow
and making it a popular haunt for thieves and bandits. Wall Road also continues
to the east.

4736.name: The Corner of Wall Road and Prince Kelmer's Mile
4736.description:
This is the point at which Prince Kelmer's Mile and Wall Road converge. The
narrow, cramped street which runs east is Wall Road, an unpopular street
with the majority of the citizens. To the south, the wider, busier street
of Prince Kelmer's Mile runs through the center of the trading district.

4737.name: The King's Parade
4737.description:
This is The King's Parade, a wide, well maintained road which connects the
two main squares of the city. Tall buildings of wood and stone line the
street on each side, many of them flying the banners of their currently
supported Lord. To the north is the Gate Square and beyond that the gates
of the city. The Parade itself continues to the south, past houses and
shops.

4738.name: The King's Parade
4738.description:
The King's Parade continues to the north and south, passing between tall,
elegant buildings. A number of trees grace the roadside, giving the street
a more presentable appearance than the rest of the city. There is a weapon
shop a short distance to the south and in the distance to the north, the
city gates can just be made out.

4739.name: Outside The King's Armaments
4739.description:
A small shop stands to the west of here, the sign outside the door naming it
as the King's Armaments, obviously a weapons shop. A sign is upon the wall
next to the shop's doorway. The parade itself leads to the north and south.
The parade is lined with trees adding to the picturesque feeling of the city.
The tall, elegant looking buildings add to the charm of the street.

4740.name: The King's Armaments
4740.description:
This large, well kept shop is obviously one of the finest weapon stores in
the city. Elegant swords and powerful looking axes hang from the walls
alongside sharp daggers and strong maces. A long wooden counter completely
dominates one wall and the exit to the shop is to the east.

4741.name: The King's Parade
4741.description:
The King's Parade comes to an end someway to the south at the large central
square of Aina, where a large number of people can be seen going about their
business. The Parade continues to the north, past tall buildings and shops
which line the street on either side. The cobblestones on the road are
well-maintained, and the street seems much more hospitable than the rest of
the city as a whole.

4742.name: Central Square
4742.description:
This large square is the centre, and meeting point of the town. Streets lead
away to the north, south and west, and the area is crowded at most hours of
the day, even late at night. The large buildings surrounding the square give
it a closed in feeling but the sound of splashing water from the stone
fountain in the middle of the square help to soothe the nerves.

4743.name: Merchant's Way
4743.description:
This narrow street is known as Merchant's way and is the traditional area
for traders and merchants to sell their wares. People crowd the street,
making it difficult to travel along, but the many shops on either side make
it the ideal place for buying equipment. Another, wider street lies to the
east running north and south.

4744.name: Merchant's Way
4744.description:
The narrow, crowded conditions of Merchant's Way make it difficult to travel
along, but the many shops and stalls along it's length make it the perfect
place to buy needed items and equipment. The sign of a mageware shop can be
seen outside a small building a short way to the west and the street
continues to the east.

4745.name: Outside the Mageware Shop
4745.description:
The sign of the star and crescent moon mark the shop to the south as a
mageware shop. That, and the intricate runes that have been carved all over
the outer walls. A small sign is upon the wall next to the doorway of the
shop. Merchant's Way continues to the east and west, all sections of the
street being crowded and cramped. Merchant's Way bends to the north a short
distance further west from here.

4746.name: Merchant's Way
4746.description:
Merchant's Way, a cluttered, busy, cramped street which runs east and west
is the centre of Aina's Trading District. It is narrow and the tall
buildings on either side cast a constant shadow during the day. The bustle
of people is a steady flow and it is hard to move along the street without
a good deal of effort. The way turns north and east from here.

4747.name: Merchant's Way
4747.description:
Merchant's Way broadens slightly here, but does little to ease the cramped
conditions evident all along the length of the street. Merchants and traders
yell out from the doorways of their shops or from the front of their carts
selling items that you couldn't imagine anyone wanting. A toothpick made
from the wood of the morgaz jungle is for sale at one cart, said to heal
the poison of the Muanga Beetle, while in another shop you can see a jar
filled with what appears to be newt's legs, the shopkeeper announcing to
all that they are the prime ingredients for a spell of protection against
the bite of a Greater Blood Beetle.

4748.name: Outside Elwinian's Armour
4748.description:
The entrance to a large, grand looking armour shop is to the west. The sign
hanging above the entrance is beautifully carved with the image of a sword
clashing against an obviously excellent suit of chain armour. The words
beneath it read: Elwinian's Armour. Merchants Way continues to the north,
through a gauntlet of traders and merchants competing with each other
to sell the citizens their goods, and it also continues to the south.

4749.name: Elwinian's Armour
4749.description:
This shop is large and obviously popular among the citizens and visitors of
the city. The interior is large and spacey, all of the items for sale being
given ample room on the display shelves and cabinets. Lamps hang from the
roof, giving the shop a bright illumination. A long wooden counter,
smooth and carefully polished takes up part of one wall. The exit to the
shop lies to the east, beyond which is Merchant's Way.

4750.name: Merchant's Way
4750.description:
Merchant's Way is a narrow, cramped street, which also serves as the centre
of the Aina Trading disctrict. Merchants and traders hawk their wares along
street at most hours of the day or night, and the area seems to be forever
congested by the throng of people all eager to view the wares. The road
continues to the north, and to the south you can see the doorway of a large
armour shop.

4751.name: The Aina Mageware Shop
4751.description:
The interior of this small shop is dark and musty, the only window being a
small, circular pane of glass on the northern wall beside the door. The
wall shelves, and indeed the entire room is filled with arcane and obviously
magical items. Jars and bottles of every shape and description fill the
shelves which seem to be everywhere in the cluttered shop. A low wooden
counter stands in the corner and the exit to the shop is to the north.

4752.name: Merchant's Way
4752.description:
This is Merchant's Way, a busy, cramped street in the Trader's District of
Aina. A throng of people mill about the area, viewing the goods on sale.
Merchants and Traders hawk their wares from carts or shop doorways, each one
trying to compete with the other and creating a confusion of noise. The
road leads to the north where it becomes Wall Street running east and west,
and south, where it passes various shops and stalls.

4753.name: Prince Kelmer's Mile
4753.description:
This is Prince Kelmer's Mile, a wide street, so named because of the Prince
who had once hidden in one of the houses when the royal family of Aina was
massacred in a revolt. The road is clean and presentable and is traditionally
the street where the city's traders make their homes. The mile continues
to the south and to the north where it meets wall road, a narrow street
which follows the city wall to the east.

4754.name: Prince Kelmer's Mile
4754.description:
Prince Kelmer's Mile is intersected here by another short road known as Royal
Way which runs to the west. The Mile itself leads to the north and to
the south, between rows of tall, presentable houses, the homes of merchants,
traders and craftsmen. Trees have been planted at various intervals along
the roadside, and add to the charm of the street. Some distance to the north
is an intersection where the Mile joins up with Wall Road that leads away
to the east.

4755.name: Prince Kelmer's Mile
4755.description:
This is Prince Kelmer's Mile, a wide pleasant street in the trading
district of Aina. Though there are few shops along the street, it is
traditionally where merchants and traders make their homes, and as such,
many of the houses are large and expensive looking, with bold, impressive
fronts that catch the eye. The street leads away to the north and the south.

4756.name: Royal Way
4756.description:
This short, narrow street is known as Royal Way and serves to connect Prince
Kelmer's Mile, which is to the east, and Prince Kelmer's Square to the west.
The road is narrow but several tall, beautiful buildings stand at the
roadside, overshadowing the street during most of the daylight hours.

4757.name: Prince Kelmer's Square
4757.description:
This small square is known as Prince Kelmer's Square after the young prince
who was known to have frequented the tavern here in secret. The tavern in
question stands to the north, a small, cozy looking building between two
tall houses. The sign outside the door reads: The Ogre's Noggin. On the
southern side of the square is a small supply shop, known as Orin's
Supplies. A sign is upon the wall next to the doorway of the store. A short,
narrow street leads away from the square to the east.

4758.name: The Ogre's Noggin
4758.description:
This small inn seems more suited to a country lane than a busy port city
such as Aina. A small fire burns in the hearth and the lanterns placed
around the walls give the room a healthy glow. The patrons talk amongst
themselves goodnaturedly and raise their glasses in greeting. Although not
particularly busy, the inn seems more full than it actually is. A doorway
leads from the tavern to the south.

4759.name: Kel's Supplies
4759.description:
This small, tidy shop is known as Kel's Supplies. Various items line the
walls, everything the average traveler would need, from waterskins to
lanterns. The room is light and several large windows look out the front of
the shop onto the square. A doorway on the same wall leads from the building
onto Prince Kelmer's Square.

4760.name: Prince Kelmer's Mile
4760.description:
This long, wide street is known as Prince Kelmer's Mile and runs all the way
through the trading district of the city. Large, expensive buildings line
the street on each side, each one seeming more impressive than the last.
Looking north, a short street can be seen intersecting this one and leading
to the west.

4761.name: Prince Kelmer's Mile
4761.description:
Prince Kelmer's Mile narrows slightly here as it approaches the city stables
a short distance to the south. The road itself runs to the north and south,
lined by tall houses and, in places, rows of trees. The road is in a good
state of repair, despite the considerable traffic it seems to receive, and
the people in view appear proud of the road.

4762.name: Outside the Aina Stables
4762.description:
The Aina stables are to the east of here, large double doors marking the
entrance. The snorting of animals and the odd clip of their hooves drift
in the air coming from beyond the entrance. Prince Kelmer's Mile, leads
to the north and south from here, the street widening slightly in both
directions.

4763.name: The Aina Stables
4763.description:
These are the Aina stables, some of the finest in the land. They are big,
with dozens of stalls along either side of the central alley. The sounds
of animals snorting softly, as well as the occasional hoof clop fill the
air. A layer of hay covers the floor, and despite the building's use,
it smells surpisingly pleasant. Large double doors lead out onto
the street to the west.

4764.name: Stable storeroom
4764.description: This is the Aina stables storeroom

4765.name: The Corner of Two Streets
4765.description:
This is Prince Kelmer's Mile, a long, narrow road which runs north and south
through the trading district of Aina. Another, wider and more elegant
road leads away to the east, tall buildings and beautiful trees lining the
street on either side.

4766.name: The King's Parade
4766.description:
This is close to the end of King's Parade, and slightly to the west can
be seen the point where Prince Kelmer's Mile connects to this road, leading
north and south. The Parade itself also leads to the east, past exquisite
buildings and shops, which stand out against the rest of the city like
gold in a pauper's hut.

4767.name: The King's Parade
4767.description:
King's Parade leads to the east and west from here, tall, elegant,
gothic-looking buildings line the street on either side. Trees have been
planted outside many of the houses and shops, and they add to the charm
and grace of the road. Slightly to the east can be seen another, smaller
street leading away from the parade to the south.

4768.name: An Intersection on The King's Parade
4768.description:
Another broad street intersects The King's Parade at this point and leads
away south. A sign on the corner of the street states it to be Wharf Street.
The scent of the ocean is filling the air, wafting up from the south.
The King's Parade continues to the east past the city's bank and west
deeper into town.

4769.name: Outside Ershin's Repairs
4769.description:
To the north is a large building, a sign outside the door naming it as
Ershin's Repairs. The building is of solid construction, the bottom half
being made from blocks of stone and the top half a mixture of both wood
and stone. The King's Parade leads to the east and the west, between tall,
and expensive looking buildings.

4770.name: The King's Parade
4770.description:
This wide, tree-lined street is known as The King's Parade and is the most
impressive street in the city. Tall, well-built buildings stand on either
side of the street, overshadowing the road like an overprotective parent.
There is no sign of litter on the street and the people that can be seen
all well dressed and are obviously of noble blood to judge from their
regal standing. The road leads to the east and the west, and an open
doorway leads north into a large, ornate building, the golden sign on
the wall proclaiming it as the Aina Branch of the Bank of Darkstone.

4771.name: The King's Parade
4771.description:
The King's Parade bends to the west here, but appears no less impressive
than the rest of the street. The people that walk by on the road are
fashionably dressed in expensive clothes and extravagant finery. The
buildings too are impressive, and the great gothic and stone fronts give the
street a sense of grandeur that cannot be found anywhere else in Aina.

4772.name: The King's Parade
4772.description:
King's Parade is a wide, tree lined street which runs north and south
through Aina's Centre. The street bends to the west someway to the south,
but continues onwards to the north where it meets up eventually with Central
Square which can be seen in the distance. The buildings on either side of
the street seem to be vying with each other to become the largest, most
impressive buildings in the city. It seems as though each one is more
marvelous than the last.

4773.name: The King's Parade
4773.description:
This is the southern stretch of The King's Parade, leading south between
tall, elegant buildings, and lines of trees which have been planted along
the roadside. To the north is the Central Square, a large, busy area that
is Aina's busy centre. The road is in good repair and seems to be kept up
well, bustling as it is.

4774.name: The End of Prince Kelmer's mile
4774.description:
This is the end of Prince Kelmer's Mile. From here, Crown Lane leads to the
west, into the richer section of the city. Looking along the street, huge
towering buildings, each one seeming to be bigger and more impressive
flank each side. Towers and minarets jut upwards from the more amazing of
the houses and shops. Prince Kelmer's Mile leads to the north, into and
through the trading district.

4775.name: Crown Lane
4775.description:
This is Crown Lane, a street which leads through the rich district of Aina.
Each of the splendid houses and shops at the roadside are in excellent
condition, each one tall and wide. Trees line the road on each side, well-
pruned olive trees and other more exotic varieties. The street is clean and
the cobbles are perfectly even, none of them cracked or missing. To the
south, another, shorter road leads from this one and to the east is the
end of Prince Kelmer's Mile which leads to the north.

4776.name: Crown Lane
4776.description:
This is Crown Lane, the primary street through Aina's Rich District. Each
of the buildings on the road is impressive in the extreme, many of them
stretching as far back as can be seen, and rising up four of five floors.
Huge oak doors and heavy iron knockers are popular on many of the houses
and others have private gardens and terraces on each of the windows. The
street leads to the east and west.

4777.name: Outside the King's Armoury
4777.description:
This is Crown Lane, a wide, beautiful street which runs through the Rich
District of the city. To the north stands a large, sturdy building, a sign
outside the door reading: The King's Armoury. Crown Lane itself leads to the
east and west from here.

4778.name: The King's Armoury
4778.description:
This large, well-outfitted shop is The King's Armoury, a specialist weapons
shop. Various items line the shelves and racks, each of them in perfect
condition and looking deadly. The muted light gleams off sword blades and
the edges of axes. A door to the south leads out of the shop and onto
Crown Lane.

4779.name: The End of Crown Lane
4779.description:
This is the end of Crown Lane, the road coming to stop at a brick wall
that is overgrown with blooming ivy vines. The most expensive and impressive
looking houses stand at this end of the street, away from the busy sectors
of the city, and it is a good guess that the owners of the houses are Lords
or other important people. The street leads to the east from here.

4780.name: Ershim's Repairs
4780.description:
This dusty, gloomy shop is Ershim's Repairs. Tools and workbenches fill
every available inch of space in the room, and various items to be repaired
are stacked at the back of the shop. The small window on the southern wall
lets in little light and the lantern hanging from the roof casts strange
shadows about the room. The exit to the shop stands to the south, leading
out onto The King's Parade.

4781.name: Noble Road
4781.description:
This short road is known as Noble Road and leads to the south from here. To
the north it connects with the bigger Crown Lane, which runs to the east
and west. This part of the city is the Rich District, and each of the
roadside buildings are huge and well-kept, many of them appearing to have
private gardens and dozens of rooms.

4782.name: Outside Tatien's Jewelry
4782.description:
This is the end of Noble Road outside a shop with a sign outside stating it
to be Tatien's Jewelry. The windows are filled with displays of the shops
wares, diamonds, and gold galore. An ornate sign is upon the wall next to
the doorway of the store. Noble Road runs to the north from here, where it
eventually joins Crown Way.

4783.name: Tatien's Jewelry
4783.description:
This plush, well-stocked shop is Tatien's Jewelry, the best supplier of
quality jewelry in Aina, according to the sign on the counter. Each of the
items on sale are kept locked in display cabinets. Everything from brooches
to ear hoops are for sale, each one gleaming in the bright light of the
shop. The exit stands to the west, leading out onto Noble Road.

4784.name: Wharf Street
4784.description:
This small street is known as Wharf Street and leads, surprisingly enough,
to the Aina docks. The smell of the sea is strong from here and you can even
spot a seagull hovering gracefully above the rooftops. To the south you can
see another, wider street leading east, while to the north is the King's
Parade, a long, broad street which runs east and west.

4785.name: Outside Rugan's Clothing
4785.description:
This is the end of Sailor's Walk, a wide street which leads to the city docks
someway to the east. A small shop stands to the east, an old sign outside
the door reading: Rugan's Clothing. It appears to be nothing special but
likes like it might hold a good selection of items. A small sign is on the
wall next to the doorway of the shop. Another, smaller road leads to the north.

4786.name: Rugan's Clothing
4786.description:
This small shop seems to be the only one located on this street. Though
small, it does seem to hold a large amount of quality clothing, much of it
in the current style of Aina. There are windows on two out of the four walls
and the room is light and airy. The doorway to the east leads out onto
Sailor's Walk.

4787.name: Sailor's Walk
4787.description:
This street is known as Sailor's Walk, as it is the only street to lead into
the heart of Aina from the city docks. Most of the buildings along the
street are warehouses, and they are large, solid looking constructions that
stand back from the road. The walk continues to the east where you can here
the sound of the waves and smell the salt air, and west towards another
smaller street, and a small shop you can see at the end of the road.

4788.name: Sailor's Walk
4788.description:
This wide street is Sailor's walk, and leads to and from the dock area of
Aina. Warehouses and storage buildings stand on the sides of the road, most
of them shuttered up tight. This area appears unpopular with the local people,
mainly due to the tough sorts you see along the road, and the big, burly
sailors. The road leads east and west from here.

4789.name: Sailor's Walk
4789.description:
The road narrows here where several of the warehous buildings at the
roadside have been built jutting forwards into the street. Looking east you
can just see the glint of the sea and the masts of one of the ships
currently at dock. The smell of the ocean is strong from here and you can
hear the gulls crying clearly. Sailor's Way leads both east and west.

4790.name: Outside the Buccaneer's Lodge
4790.description:
A large tavern stands to the south, the first traditional stopping point
for sailors on leave. It is a solid wooden construction with a tall ships'
mast on the roof for effect, a seagull currently perched on the crow's nest.
A sign swinging outside the door reads: The Buccaneer's Lodge. Judging from
the noise from within you assume it is popular. Sailor's Way leads east to
the docks, and west towards Aina's centre.

4791.name: Sailor's Walk
4791.description:
You are approaching the wharf which can be seen some distance to the east,
the shine of the sea just beyond it. The fresh seabreeze is strong here
and there are a number of seagulls circling in the air above the docks. The
road leads east, towards the docks, and west towards Aina, pasing a large
tavern at the roadside.

4792.name: Within the Buccaneer's Lodge
4792.description:
This is the large common room of the Buccaneer's Lodge, a tavern near the
Aina docks. The patrons all appear to be sailors or dock workers and they
all seem to regard you with some suspicion. Thick wreathes of smoke cloud
the air, giving you the feeling you are standing in fog rather than a
tavern. The room is well furnished, the tables and walls fashioned from
polished oak. The clanking of ale tankards, the gruff voices of sailors
raised in singing ballads, and the scuffle of furniture are all everpresent
noises, giving the tavern an atmosphere unlike any other in the city. The
doorway to the north leads out onto Sailor's Way.

4793.name: Sailor's Walk
4793.description:
This is the end of Sailor's Walk, travelling east bringing you onto the
Wharf. The sea is clearly visible beyond the docks, the light shining off
the clear blue waters. The area is busy with sailors but most of them seem
to ignore you, going about their business. Sailor's Way continues to the west,
leading towards the centre of Aina.

4794.name: South Wharf
4794.description:
This is South Wharf, the southern part of the walkway around the docks.
Leading west from here is Sailor's Walk, which leads into the city of Aina.
The sea is clear and bright, the sun sparkling off the water, and small
waves break gently against the sea wall below the wharf. Looking towards
the city you can see the tops of the buildings standing against the backdrop
of the Pardor mountains in the distance. The wharf leads to the north and
south from here.

4795.name: South Wharf
4795.description:
This is South Wharf, part of the Aina docks. The sea is clear and fresh,
and the tangy taste of salt is heavy on the breeze. Boats and ships are
moored in the docks, some of them merchant ships, others belonging to
Lords or rich traders. There are also smaller boats tied up against the sea
wall, most of them obviously fishing vessels. The Wharf leads to the north
and south from here.

4796.name: South Wharf
4796.description:
The smell of the sea is strong and there is the taste of salt heavy on the
air. A strong breeze blows along the wharf and you can hear the waves
rolling gently against the sea wall below the walkway. Out in the port you
can see ships and boats moored in place and beyond them, the wide open
sea, glinting brightly in the sunlight. The Wharf leads to the north and
the south from here.

4797.name: South Wharf
4797.description:
This is South Wharf, a wooden walkway around the Aina docks. Looking out
over the bay there is nothing but sea for miles, the port itself dotted
with ships and boats. Seagulls circle in the air, diving down for the
occassional scrap of food. The call of sailors and captains mingle with the
crashing of the waves against the sea wall below the wharf. South Wharf
continues to the north and the south.

4798.name: South Wharf
4798.description:
You are on South Wharf, the wooden walkway that leads onto the city docks.
Just east of here, one of the docking platforms leads out to sea where
a large ship is currently moored. The wharf itself leads to the north and
south, following the top of the sea wall.

4799.name: The End of the Wharf
4799.description:
This is the end of South Wharf, the wooden walkway that makes up part of the
Aina docks. Looking out across the bay, the water sparkles and gleams,
glinting brightly in the light. The air is fresh and tangy, the taste of
salt heavy in the air. Gulls circle above, their calls mingling with the
cries of sailors and ship's masters working on their vessels. The wharf
continues to the north from here.

4800.name: South Dock
4800.description:
This is the southern dock of Aina, and looking out along the platform, it
appears that a large ship is currently moored at it. Looking out beyond the
ship you can see the large bay which makes up the city docks. Ships and
boats bob on the water, most of them unable to find docking space and
resorting to mooring in the bay and sending small boats in to land their
goods or passengers. To the west of here is south Wharf, which leads to
the north and south.

4801.name: South Dock
4801.description:
This is the end of the South Dock. Going any further east would bring you
aboard a large ship which is currently moored here. The name painted on the
side of the ship reads: Maiden of the Sea. Beyond the ship is the bay and
then nothing but wide open water, as far as the eye can see. The view is
breathtaking, with the tall cliff coast rising up either side of the neck
of the bay.

4802.name: The Corner of South and Buccaneer's Wharf
4802.description:
This is the corner of South Wharf and Buccaneer's Wharf, the fronts of the
Aina dock. Buccaneer's leads to the east, away from the city, while South
Wharf heads further inwards, towards Aina. Looking out across the docks,
it is possible to see for miles, with nothing on the horizon except the
Great Sea. Ships and boats bob gently in the bay, several of them moored at
the docks.

4803.name: Buccaneer's Wharf
4803.description:
At one time, this stretch of the sea wall was a prime spot for smugglers,
as a number of caves in the cliff face, which is now the sea wall, led into
the city sewers. With the creation of the sea wall and the Dark Watch, the
practices all but disappeared from the docks but the name Buccaneer's Wharf
stuck. The walkway leads to the east, towards one of the docking platforms
and west, where another wharf leads to the south.

4804.name: Buccaneer's Wharf
4804.description:
This walkway is known as Buccaneer's Wharf and runs east and west along
the Aina docks. The whole dock area is busy at all hours with sailors and
workers hurrying about their business. Ships bustle in and out of the bay,
from huge war galleys to small, speedy trading vessels. There are even tiny
fishing boats belonging to local men tied up along the sea wall.

4805.name: Buccaneer's Wharf
4805.description:
Buccaneer's Wharf leads to the east and west here, along the northern part
of the Aina docks. The wharf was built on top of the sea wall, a large
stone structure built to keep the city safe from the terrible waves that
arise during winter storms. For as far as you can see beyond the docks,
there is nothing but water, the sun glinting of the surface.

4806.name: Buccaneer's Wharf
4806.description:
Buccaneer's Wharf leads to the east and west from here, following the top
of the Sea Wall. The northern side of the street is taken up with warehouses
where goods brought into the city by sea are stored. The buildings are
large and well built, but with little imagination. The view out to sea is
incredible. Dozens of boats and ships bob on the water of the bay, and
beyond that, the wide open sea shimmers in the light, like a vast moving
carpet of silver.

4807.name: Buccaneer's Wharf
4807.description:
The Wharf leads east and west, following the top of the Sea Wall which is
built beneath the wooden walkway. Gulls and other sea birds circle in the
air looking for scraps of food, their calls ringing out and mingling with
the background noises of the docks. Sailors and other sea faring folk
walk the docks, as well as merchants and traders who make their livings
travelling from port to port.

4808.name: Buccaneer's Wharf
4808.description:
The Wharf leads to the east and west from here. The salty taste of the sea
is strong and the faint breeze carries with it the bittersweet promise of
exotic adventures in far off lands, and the experience of life at sea. The
Great Sea spreads out and away as far as you can see, the light glinting
brightly off the water and making it seem like a shimmering carpet of
silver. Boats, ships and trading vessels fill the bay and their is the
occassional curse or bellow as a captain tries to squeeze past another
ship blocking the neck of the bay.

4809.name: Buccaneer's Wharf
4809.description:
This is Buccaneer's Wharf, a wooden walkway which leads east and west, along
the northern section of the Aina docks. Along the northern edge of the
street are the city warehouses, holding points for various wares which are
brought in and out of the city by sea. On the other side of the street is
the start of one of the docking platforms which leads out to sea a short
way. Beyond that is nothing but a sheer drop down to the water.

4810.name: Buccaneer's Wharf
4810.description:
This is the end of Buccaneer's Wharf. Moving any further east or south
from here would result in a long drop down to the waters of the sea. You
can travel further west, passing one of the docking platforms and the
big Aina Warehouses which are built alongside the wharf. From here the view
out to sea is almost perfect, looking along the coastline across nothing
but shimmering water.

4811.name: North Dock
4811.description:
This narrow, wooden platform is the northern dock. Ships and large vessels
weigh anchor at this point in order to deliver goods or passengers to the
city. To the north of here is the Buccaneer's Wharf, a long walkway which
follows the top of the Sea Wall, the barrier which keeps the waters of
the sea from flooding the city. The dock continues a short distance to the
south from here.

4812.name: North Dock
4812.description:
This is the end of the north dock. Looking down beyond the edge of the
platform you can see the swirling waters of the see far below. A drop to
the water from here would be dangerous indeed and possibly even fatal. The
dock leads to the north, towards Buccaneer's Wharf.

4813.name: On the 'Maiden of the Sea'
4813.description:
This is the upper deck of a large ship named the 'Maiden of the Sea'. It is
in good condition, with the deck polished and clean. The mast rears up from
the centre of the ship, with the crows nest at a dizzying height. The
gangplank leads from the ship to the east onto the Aina docks and you
can expore the ship in most other directions.

4814.name: On the 'Maiden of the Sea'
4814.description:
The tall wooden mast rears up from the deck here, and looking up, you can
see the crows nest some distance above, at a dizzying height. The deck of
the 'Maiden' spreads out to the north, south and west. You can also climb
the mast using hand rails which are cut into the wood.

4815.name: On the 'Maiden of the Sea'
4815.description:
This fine ship is named the 'Maiden of the Sea'. The deck is polished and
shiny and all of the wood is in good condition and well tended. A small
railing surrounds the ship, to serve as protection against drunken crew
members tumbling overboard. The front of the ship is to the northeast, a
statue of a beautiful, buxom woman on the prow.

4816.name: On the 'Maiden of the Sea'
4816.description:
This is the deck of a large, ocean going vessel which is currently moored
in the Aina docks. While not the biggest in the port, it is certainly one
of the finest, with a tall mast, polished deck, and rigging which is kept
in a perfect condition.

4817.name: The Prow of the Ship
4817.description:
The prow of the ship reaches high out of the water, the two sides of the
ship joining to make a sharp point which cuts through the water easily.
A statue of a woman with long, silver hair is fixed to the prow, and you
wonder if she is the 'maiden' in the ship's name. The deck of the ship
spreads out to the southeast and southwest.

4818.name: On the 'Maiden of the Sea'
4818.description:
You are on the deck of the Maiden of the Sea, a large ship which is currently
at port in the Aina docks. The wood is in good condition, polished and
free from crack or splinters. The gentle swaying of the ship causes the
hull to creak quietly. You can move around the ship in most directions.

4819.name: On the 'Maiden of the Sea'
4819.description:
A ladder leads downwards here, into what you assume is the ship's cabins.
It is too dark to make out any details from here. The deck of the ship
spreads out to the north, west and south, while to the east is the waters
of the ocean, gleaming in the light like a great silver carpet.

4820.name: On the 'Maiden of the Sea'
4820.description:
This is the rear end of the large, ocean going ship known as the 'Maiden
of the Sea'. A wooden rail surrounds the back of the ship and the rest of
the deck spreads out to the north and east. Looking over the rail, you
see it is a large drop down to the waters below.

4821.name: On the 'Maiden of the Sea'
4821.description:
This is the stern of the ship, a tall railing serving as the only barrier
between you and the ocean, some distance below. The ship appears to be a
fine vessel, kept in an immaculate condition by the crew. Some way to the
north, the mast rises up into the air with the crows nest near the top.
The deck of the ship spreads out from here to the north and the west.

4822.name: Climbing the Mast
4822.description:
This is the bottom section of the ships mast. Some way above you can see
the crows nest, a round platform encircled by a wooden railing. The mast
has brackets cut into it's surface to make climbing easier, but it is still
a tiring task. Looking down you can see the deck of the 'maiden'.

4823.name: Climbing the Mast
4823.description:
This is halfway up the ships mast. Looking from this height you can see
across the rooftops of the city and far out to see, where a few ships are
moving away from the port. A short distance above is the crows nest, while
the deck is some way below you.

4824.name: In the Crow's Nest
4824.description:
This is the crows nest at the top of the ship's mast. From here, the crew
member on watch duty can see for miles around and spot other ships or land
easily. A small railing surrounds the platform and brackets in the mast
serve as a ladder to reach the deck some distance below.

exdescs.up:
The stars sparkle across the velvet night sky, shimmering in their formations.
To the north the Tiger constellation sparkles above the Pardor mountains.
The right eye of the tiger is an unusual star, it seems to be encircled by two
golden rings and shines brighter than all the rest.

4825.name: In the Cargo Hold
4825.description:
This is the ship's cargo hold, a small, cramped space in the hull of the
'maiden'. Crates and boxes of all shapes and sizes fill the area, with only
a narrow space leading to the north and west. A wooden ladder leads upwards
into daylight, the sound of the sea coming through the small opening.

4827.name: Prince Kelmer's Mile
4827.description:
This is Prince Kelmer's Mile, a wide, well-kept street which runs north and
south. To the north an intersection with The King's Parade can be seen,
another wide, elegant road which leads to the east. This road continues
further to the south, ending eventually at Crown Lane, a road through the
wealthy distric of the city.

4828.name: Prince Kelmer's Mile
4828.description:
Just south of here, Prince Kelmer's Mile ends at a wide, tree-lined street
known as Crown Lane, which runs through the rich district of Aina. The Mile
itself has elegant looking buildings, each one tall and magnificent. The
road continues to the north, traveling through the trading district, and it
is because of this that the majority of the houses belong to merchants or
rich traders who make their livings plying their wares on Merchant's Way.

4829.name: The First Mate's Cabin
4829.description:
This is the small cabin belonging to the first mate. A number of shelves
have been built into the wall of the room, each one holding various trinkets
and items belonging to the ships mate. A wide birth is attached to the far
wall, the covering sheets made up neatly. A doorway leads from the cabin
into the cargo hold to the east.

4830.name: The Captain's Cabin
4830.description:
This is the largest cabin on the ship and belongs to the captain of the
vessel. Charts and maps cover a wooden table in the centre of the room along
with a number of navigational tools and instruments. A bookshelf stands
against one wall with the captains birth on the far one. A door to the south
leads out into the cargo hold.

4831.name: Prince Kelmer's Mile
4831.description:
This road is known as Prince Kelmer's Mile and runs to the north and south,
through the Aina trading district. To the north lie the city's stables,
the road narrowing slightly as it passes by them. To the south is an
intersection with with another road that eventually leads off to the east.

4832.name: The Gardener's Hut
4832.description:
This small wooden hut serves as the working space of the Gardener. Tools
are lined neatly on the walls and a workbench along the back wall holds
a number of potted flowers and plants. A round window on each wall gives
a clear view of the beautiful gardens outside, and the door to the north
leads out of the hut.

exdescs.crack:
Amazingly symmetrical, this crack is shaped like a large arch.  A small
hole sits in the center of the arch.
exdescs.long:
Amazingly symmetrical, this crack is shaped like a large arch.  A small
hole sits in the center of the arch.

4833.name: Entrance to the Aina Gardens
4833.description:
This wide gate marks the entrance to the Aina Gardens. Looking through the
gates, small brick paths can be seen leading through the flowers and plants
which make up the various displays. There are different animals wandering
among the gardens, many of them belonging to rare and unique species. To
the north is Crown Lane, a street in the rich district of the city.

4834.name: Within the Aina Gardens
4834.description:
Quaint brick paths leads among the flowers and beautiful plants which make
up the scenic gardens. The peace and quiet make it seem that the visitors
to the gardens are really many leagues away, and not in the center of a
busy port city. The various displays are well thought out and give off
a glorious scent.

4835.name: Within the Aina Gardens
4835.description:
Wandering among the flowers and plants, there appear to be many exotic
varieties brought from all over the world to adorn the Aina gardens. From
tall, red plants, to small, silver and gold flowers, everything melds into
one beautiful tapestry of colour and smell, which goes with the peace and
quiet to create an amazing feeling of contentment.

4836.name: Within the Aina Gardens
4836.description:
This corner of the gardens is made up of blues and reds to create a
stunning tapestry of colour. The smell too is amazing, bringing up
images of far away lands and cultures. Small paths weave through the
flowers and plants to the east and south, leading to other displays of
equal beauty and colour.

4837.name: Beside a Rockery
4837.description:
Rocks of all shapes, sizes and colours have been arranged here to create
a small rock garden. Miniature crags and cliffs provide support for the
strategically placed plants and flowers around the rockery. A small stream
of water trickles over the top of the rocks forming a tiny waterfall.

4840.name: Within the Flower Garden
4840.description:
This is the very centre of the gardens and has been reserved for the
greatest and most beautiful of the displays. The earth has been piled up
to create a small mound, ontop of which has been arranged an incredible
selection of the most beautiful flowers and plants in the garden. Reds,
greens, blues and yellows mingle with tall, swaying plants the permeate the
air with breathtaking smells.

4841.name: Within the Flower Garden
4841.description:
Paths meander through the displays of flowers and plants. They are laid in
such a way as to appear natural among the displays. The smells and sights
of the garden are breathtaking, with incredible scenes of colour and beauty
all around.

4842.name: Within the Flower Garden
4842.description:
This is the southern end of the garden, where the plants and flowers are
so vividly coloured and varied that they seem almost to have been thrown
together carelessly. The effect is stunning on the senses, and the scent
is incredibly powerful, seeming bothe exotic and natural at once.

4843.name: A Sparkling Pond and Waterfall
4843.description:
A small mound of rocks rise up here, a small stream at the top cascading
down to form a waterfall. Looking into the pool at the bottom, one
can see the shiny backs of several rainbow fish swimming lazily to
and fro. Flowers have been arranged up the side of the cliff, providing
a strange, yet beautiful contrast to the stark gray of the rock.

4844.name: Within the Flower Gardens
4844.description:
Flowers and plants merge into one beautiful cascade of colour and scent,
providing an amazing, beautiful display of nature. Flowers from all over
the world have been brought here to create the most spectacular gardens
in existence. A brilliant splash of red, gold, green, yellow and blue all
mix into one, giving the impression of walking through a mad splash of
paint, or a rainbow instead of a garden.

4845.name: A Stone Bridge Over a Stream
4845.description:
A small, quaint stone bridge spans a quietly gurgling stream. The water is
shallow and lined with aquatic plants. Tiny fish can be seen swimming lazily
upstream. More flowers of every shape, colour and size line the banks of
the stream along with one or two small trees who's branches overhang the
water in places. The main gardens are to the east, and a garden of roses
is found to the west.

4846.name: The Rose Garden
4846.description:
This small corner of the garden is given over to roses of all types. The
rare white rose which is found only in the highest peaks of pardor, to the
brilliant sand rose, found in the great desert. The flowers sway in the
breeze, like a rippling, many coloured sea. A stone bridge leads over a
small stream to the east.

4847.name: The Aina Branch of the Bank of Darkstone
4847.description:
This room is filled with everything that could be considered
ostentatious. Grand marble desks are in use by the bank's employees,
intricate colorful mosaics cover the walls, and the ceiling has been
painted with majestic scenes of the city. Wealthy citizens fill
the room, as they go about their banking transactions. A heavy iron
door has been set into the northern wall, and is secured with an
enormous lock. A doorway in the southern wall leads onto The King's
Parade.

4849.name: Upon a Stone Ledge
4849.description:
The ledge below is just wide enough for a single person to stand
upon safely. The sea wall extends in either direction to the west
and east along the shoreline, keeping the city safe from the constant
beatings of the ocean. The actual wall in this location seems to
be made of pretty standard sized stones, for the most part. The ledge
can be followed to the east to a set of stairs that have been
carved into the wall that lead back up to the wharf.

exdescs.stone:
One stone in particular catches the eye, it is much smaller
than all the rest, and seems to be centered perfectly in this
section of wall, at just the right height to be pushed.

4850.name: Entrance to a Smuggler's Den
4850.description:
This room has been built within the sea wall, most probably at
the time that the wall was originally built. What ever purpose
it may have been intented for then, now, it looks to be part of
of a smuggler's den. Central in the room is a rickety desk and
chair. The desk is covered with maps of the coastline in this
area and of the layouts of Aina and a few other cities. Piled
up around the edges of the room are boxes and chests that are
laden with stolen booty, most probably filched from local
warehouses or ships that have docked at the wharf. A doorway
leads further into the den to the north, and the exit back to
the ledge is through the door to the south.

4851.name: A Hallway in the Den
4851.description:
This short hallway leads from the entrance to the den at the south,
back to two other rooms. A room to the west is behind an ornate oaken
door. Upon the door is carved a large ship, flying a flag of the skull
and crossbones. The room to the east is behind a locked door of iron.
Upon the door, is an intricate locking mechanism that looks like it
is missing a circular piece of it. Whatever is behind that door, the
smugglers are wanting to keep locked up and safe.

4852.name: Smugglers Leader's Office
4852.description:
The leader of the smugglers has obviously picked through the
best of the booty to get the items to decorate his office.
Ornate oil lamps hang from the walls which have been paneled
in a dark wood paneling. Upon the floor a large intricately
woven tapestry rug lies covering up the stone floor. An
elaborately carved oaken desk and chair sit at the northern
section of the room and an enormous map of the coastline
hangs upon the western wall.

4853.name: Smuggler's Cache
4853.description:
The walls of this cache have been lined in iron, to keep out
anyone who would want to try to steal the smuggler's booty.
Situated all throughout the room are spoils taken from visiting
ships and from warehouses of this and other cities. Items
stored in this room include weapons, fabrics, spices, gold, and
most any other item of value that the smugglers can sell.

4854.name: Inside the Wall
4854.description:
This is a passage that is hidden within this wall. The air has
a very musty odor to it, and is filled with dust and debris that
has been stirred up from the intrusion. A faint light is coming
from the north, further down the passage.

4855.name: A Room Within the Wall
4855.description:
It looks like this room hasn't been visited in many years. A
fine layer of dust covers what few objects are lying around,
an old box that looks like it was used as a table and some
broken wood that might have been a chair in a former life that
is piled up in the corner. An exit from this room is through the
wall to the south.

4856.name: Aina Mob Holding Room
4856.description: The shopkeepers from Aina come here to sleep.

4857.name: In Betwixt the Brick Walls
4857.description:
This is a very odd place indeed.  On all four sides, are brick walls.
The ceiling is covered, and the floor is brick too.  Mounted on the
wall is a single torch.  There is nothing else in this space.
